04225nam a22005535i 9780822391623DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20102010ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223916237 a10.1515/97808223916232doi  a(DE-B1597)554255  a(OCoLC)1202624776  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a304.22221 aBennett, Jane, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aVibrant Matter :bA Political Ecology of Things /cJane Bennett. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2010] 4cÂ©2010  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aA John Hope Franklin Center Book00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. The Force of Things -- t2. The Agency of Assemblages -- t3. Edible Matter -- t4. A Life of Metal -- t5. Neither Vitalism nor Mechanism -- t6. Stem Cells and the Culture of Life -- t7. Political Ecologies -- t8. Vitality and Self-interest -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Vibrant Matter the political theorist Jane Bennett, renowned for her work on nature, ethics, and affect, shifts her focus from the human experience of things to things themselves. Bennett argues that political theory needs to do a better job of recognizing the active participation of nonhuman forces in events. Toward that end, she theorizes a "vital materiality" that runs through and across bodies, both human and nonhuman. Bennett explores how political analyses of public events might change were we to acknowledge that agency always emerges as the effect of ad hoc configurations of human and nonhuman forces. She suggests that recognizing that agency is distributed this way, and is not solely the province of humans, might spur the cultivation of a more responsible, ecologically sound politics: a politics less devoted to blaming and condemning individuals than to discerning the web of forces affecting situations and events.Bennett examines the political and theoretical implications of vital materialism through extended discussions of commonplace things and physical phenomena including stem cells, fish oils, electricity, metal, and trash. She reflects on the vital power of material formations such as landfills, which generate lively streams of chemicals, and omega-3 fatty acids, which can transform brain chemistry and mood. Along the way, she engages with the concepts and claims of Spinoza, Nietzsche, Thoreau, Darwin, Adorno, and Deleuze, disclosing a long history of thinking about vibrant matter in Western philosophy, including attempts by Kant, Bergson, and the embryologist Hans Driesch to name the "vital force" inherent in material forms. Bennett concludes by sketching the contours of a "green materialist" ecophilosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aEnvironmentalismxPhilosophy. 0aHuman ecologyxPhilosophy. 0aHuman ecologyxPolitical aspects. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822391623zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822391623423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822391623.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles